author: adagiofortron

description.text:
This was made for the University of Aberdeen as wind-turbine lab apparatus. Note: .mdl files were generated using Moray, and exported to OpenSCAD for compilation using the plugin which I have included in the attached files.  
The idea is that a group of students can make wind-turbine blades attached to a hub which slots onto the lego shaft, and direct a desk-fan at it. Assuming the turbine design works, it will cause the 30:1 gearbox to rotate, rotating the bobbin at the rear end of the test rig, winching up a mass of up to one kilo (tested). The time it takes to winch up the weight a given height indicates the 'power' of the turbine. Potential energy = mgh (joules I believe, but I'm rusty!), thus the height gained in 1 second can be converted to joules per second, which is Watts.   
This design is intended to have some parts printed in PLA, and other parts in ABS. It is also intended to have some parts printed with a 0.2 mm nozzle, and other parts with a 0.4 mm nozzle! Each file has its intended print conditions at the end of the filename. e.g. ABS_0.4_0.2 indicates to print in ABS with a 0.4 mm nozzle, and 0.2 mm build layers.

Some parts should be printed in PLA, others in ABS. The PLA parts are meant to be printed with a 0.2 mm nozzle. The end of each filename in the STL files indicates the print mode. E.g.  
ABS_0.4_0.2  
indicates 0.4 mm print nozzle, 0.2 mm slice layers, and print in ABS.  
PLA_0.2_0.1  
indicates 0.2 mm print nozzle, 0.1 mm layers and PLA.  
The shopping list for this thing is currently incomplete... but when I get a chance I'll add one! For now, best just download the instructions and make your own list of necessary parts before you begin printing. The instructions are in the attached RAR files, and consist of many pictures!

description.text:
Note: Please read the post-processing section for instructions and precautions, since I'm not responsible for any damages that occur to your telescope:)

I designed this mount to manage cables on my iOptron CEM25 that connect to my PC and run up to the guide camera and DSLR. The cable mount is designed for a 90mm diameter tube (as in the physical diameter of the scope, not the aperture, its the same diameter that your scope rings are made for). I currently have it installed on a Celestron C80ED. There are 3 different pieces to the mount, the upper ring, lower ring, and the cable runner cover. I designed it so that the upper and lower rings are connected using 2 M3x12mm bolts going through the top ring and screwing into M3 nuts on the bottom ring. I chose to use M3's for the small size, as I designed this to print fast. There is also a nut insert on the bottom ring for attaching the cable runner using a M3x8mm bolt. The runner cover acts as a simple clamp to keep the cables in place (and therefore not pulling on the camera connectors).The cable mount can go anywhere along the optical tube, although I would mount it as close to the DEC axis as possible so that any torque caused by tugging cables is minimized (I would mount it closer than I did in the pictures, but Celestron's stupid clamshell ring prevented that along with other plans). It is currently designed for two cables, but if you need to mount more or if you need a different diameter, please feel free to message me and I'll try and throw something together for you.

Printer:

Tevo Tarantula

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

70%

Notes:

I printed mine flat, so you if you choose the same, you'll just need supports for the lower ring. If you have issues with the nut inserts, you could try using supports for those too, I'm not sure how fun it would be to remove those though, so you could also try scaling it up a tad. I can't guarantee it will fit as snug if you do choose to upscale it, so it'd be best to make sure you have a good layer fan.

Printed with PETG and a 0.3mm nozzle.

Precautions

1) Please make sure that when you screw the cable runner on, that the screw does not protrude out and into the telescope, as that could put a dent in it. I tried to give enough clearance so you don't need a super long bolt (8mm hopefully is long enough). I would recommend attaching the cable runner cover to the lower ring before mounting it on the OTA to make sure that it doesn't stick out (You may need to use a different length M3 bolt depending on your cable sizes)

2) Before using the mount, make sure that all of your cables still have enough length so that there's not any tugging when it slews anywhere, and that in general its movement is not restricted or anything. You may want to check the balance as well.

Post-Printing

You may want to sand the inside of the rings as well as line them with felt if you're worried about scratching your OTA. Also, the cable cutouts for the clamp may be pretty tight depending on their thickness. If this is the case (as it was for me), I would try removing the lower ring from the upper ring and then attaching the cable runner top (without the cables in it) using the bolt. Once it's snug, use a drill bit with a similar (preferable oh so slightly smaller so the clamp still grips the cables), and then carefully drilling the hole so that the cutout is wider. Careful, since the walls are thin around that area.

The best filament I've found by a large margin is sunlu white filament, it has a slightly matte/pearlescent texture which soaks up a lot more ink than regular pla which can give underwhelming results, it also makes the layer lines almost invisible and prints with a beautiful sheen. You can play with running the holder up and down the filament before it gets to the hot end to soak more ink in and get some darker layers.

description.text:
I built an emulator out of an Odroid XU4 and wanted a creative case. After trying wood, legos, and even an old thin client shell I ran into FeedMePi's N64,000 Game emulator and fell in love. I started planning on ordering the parts (I don't own a 3d Printer) and saw peterholzapfel's remix: N64 Retro Pi. I thought I could use Peter's sled and backplate designs for the Odroid XU4. What follows is the journey of the remix. I'm not very good with 3d designers so please forgive me. I give full credit to FeedMePi and Peter without whom, this project wouldn't have been possible.

Internal Components:
Odroid XU4q with eMMC card: https://ameridroid.com/products/odroid-xu4q
Bluetooth Dongle: http://a.co/iEMCG9M
4 Port USB Hub: http://a.co/1fyjpSf
Software: https://batocera-linux.xorhub.com/
Controllers: PlayStation 4 Dualshock wireless
Flash drive: http://a.co/hwS24zS
HDMI ribbon cable: http://a.co/73C1xyb
HDMI jack: https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/tripp-lite/P164-000-KP-BK/TL1042-ND/6166159
Power jack: https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/tensility-international-corp/54-00063/839-1291-ND/6206244
Ethernet jack: Some plain Cat6e keystone jack.

A dry fitting of the visible parts. Lots of imperfections in the printing. The power button is basically unusable so I'll have to re-print it. The rest I should be able to sand and fill as appropriate. I'll probably be losing the nice blue color sadly. Using keystone fittings for the hdmi and ethernet made the compartment, what is normally used for the N64's video connector, usable. Easy to assemble, this is the only place I had to "alter" the N64. I had to Dremel out areas to let the hdmi and ethernet cable to pass through. I had to drill the power hole out a bit. I started with 1/4" drill bit and kept getting bigger until the power adapter fit perfectly. The print quality of the sled was much better than the blue pieces I had printed previously. I'll be using this company again for my printing going forward. Only alterations are hollowing out the holes for the Odroid. Other than that, it fit like a glove. Backplane hooked up and ready to roll. Unfortunately I did have to do more cutting to make everything fit snug. As it sits everything works perfectly. You can see the Bluetooth adapter in the USB slot beside the ethernet port. You can also see the white 128gig flash drive in the USB3.0 slot. To support the four usb ports in the front of the N64 I had to remove the housing of the USB hub. Turns out it fits perfectly on the left once the casing is removed. The rectangle below the heatsink is the casing for the male part of the hub. It fit (totally unintended) perfectly in the space and holds the cable snugly. The hub also includes a light which I may be able to relocate to the front of the N64. it appears that the light is only on when the OS of the ODroid is loaded. More testing is needed but I think it may be a good on/off indicator light. I tried un-soldering the blue light (so I could reuse it) from the hub and just couldn't get off. But then it came to me, why not use the 5v power from the hub through USB to power an on/off light. So here is a picture of it in place (later I had to anchor it to a screw). The good part of this solution is when the OS isn't running, neither is the hub so the light goes off properly. The green light was quite bright so it had to be mounted sideways in the original N64 diffuser. After some cable management here is the complete guts. The green light took up one of the USB sockets so the extra one is just danglin'. There is also room on the right for an internal fan to be added later.

Step 1: The Odroid XU4q

I wanted to make sure the guts were going to work before going through all the crafty parts so I build the gaming part first. Everything was hooked up and configured. Batocera was configured to use the wireless PS4 controllers and to use a 128gig flash drive to serve all of my roms. Everything worked as expected. BTW, the XU4q is a powerhouse of pocket computers. It runs emulators much better than the Pi3. Sorry Pi.

Step 2: Securing the N64

I started scouring Ebay for a broke N64. Surprisingly not too many were available so I bought a working one for a very reasonable price. Yes, i'm going to gut a working N64...don't judge me. You will need a special 4.5 mm Game Bit to open the N64. (http://a.co/cp1hLbY) Make sure you keep all parts as some will be reusable.

Step 2: Designing the sled

I liked peterholzapfel's sled design. It fit snugly and seemed pretty accurate. Only one problem. The screw holes were made for a Raspberry Pi which wouldn't work for the XU4. So, I removed all of the extra Pi stuff and added the bottom of a XU4 case I found here on Thingiverse. The sled fits directly next to the case so I decided it was ok to open up the floor to give the XU some more room to breath.

Step 3: Designing the backplane

Peter also had a good backplane design that utilized the open hole on the back of the N64. I changed the adapter holes to include one for the power jack, the network jack and hdmi jack. Both hdmi and the network holes are configured to hold a keystone jack.

Step 4: Print, fit, then print again.

After everything was printed I did a dry fitting and everything fit OK. I did have to make a few changes which resulted in the .stl files in the project. I also had to hollow out a few of the screw holes but once I did, everything fit great.

Step 5: Reflection and follow up.

After all the pieces were sanded and filled, it hit me: Why am I working so hard to recreate visual pieces that already exist? So I scrapped all visual pieces except for the controller ports and used the original visual case parts. So the feet, buttons, door, and slot are all original and painted to match the controller ports. Course, after that was done I had another revelation: Why do I need to paint the original parts? Why not paint the Controller ports to match the other pieces? Oh well, hind site is better than foresight.

description.text:
This OpenSCAD (http://www.openscad.org/) script generates dodecahedra. Using a single parameter, you can go from a cube to a rhombic dodecahedron. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dodecahedron for more information. You can use the script to customize the magnet holes and the size of the tiles as well.

You'll need a total of 12 tiles, and 4 or 6 disc magnets per tile (axially magnetized). The script will figure out if 2 magnets can comfortably fit on the 'base edge' of the pentagon. Because these edges are always matched together, they cannot accommodate a single magnet in the center position. In the rhombic dodecahedron case, that edge has zero length and cannot accommodate any magnets.

Magnet orientation:
The pair of base edge magnets, if present, must have opposite polarity to each other
The edges to the left and right of the base need to have opposite polarity to each other
The 'top' edges (the 'peak') need to have opposite polarity to each other

All the tiles have to be identical with regard to the magnet alignment. A good way to keep track is to make your first tile according to the rules above, and use it as a references for every subsequent tile (test your magnets against it).

Note that for the cube and for the regular dodecahedron, the magnet pattern will not work as designed, so 'legal' placements of tiles will be sometimes repelled (we want face transitivity, but not edge transitivity for the magnet patterns to work).

Scroll to the bottom of the script to see examples that create the solid model instead, or the assembly of tiles.

I printed mine with the ReplicatorG accelerated defaults and no raft or support. They printed in about 20 minutes each.

Check it out on github: https://github.com/eshira/polyhedra

title: Distel - smooth algebraic surface
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Distel, a smooth algebraic surface of degree six. This is the set of real points for which 

x^2+y^2+z^2+1000 * (x^2+y^2)*(x^2+z^2)*(y^2+z^2)-1 = 0.

Has no holes! Has no singularities! Is actually smooth at its points! Not actually pointed! Topologically equivalent to a sphere!

I have provided these files:

  • Distel_Super_Smooth.stl -- sampled to decently tight tolerances.
  • Distel_Newsmooth.stl -- surprisingly, an older version of the sampler was used to refine it. Take the name with a grain of salt. Enjoy
  • input -- the Bertini_real input file used to compute it.

One of the first surfaces I computed with Bertini_real, in early 2014.

This surface was sampled before I implemented cyclenumber > 1 sampling, so the surface is undersampled near critical points and singularities.

Computed with a Numerical Algebraic Geometry program I wrote, called Bertini_real and printed as part of my long-term project to reproduce Herwig Hauser's gallery of algebraic surface ray-traces in my own gallery of 3d prints. The ACM ToMS algorithm number is 976; the major published paper is DOI 10.1145/3056528 with several others preceding. Bertini_real implements the implicit function theorem for algebraic surfaces and curves in any (reasonable) number of variables.

These surfaces are generally challenging to print. Rotate, and use careful support. I use Simplify3D for the manual support placement feature. These surfaces are also very tiny in scale (arbitrary units and math and all) so require significant upsizing.

See also, my Thingiverse collection of algebraic surfaces.

description.text:
Dromedar, a singular algebraic surface of degree four. This is the set of real points for which 

x^4 - 3*x^2 + y^2+z^3 = 0.

Has a single singularity, at the origin!

I have provided these files:

Since the program works in arbitrary dimensions, I make no effort to control normals from it -- they don't exist for 4- and higher-dimensional surfaces, but instead a tangent space which is not immediately useful for 3d printing. Hence, the surface was thickened in Blender, before being passed through Microsoft's 3D Builder to fix internal geometry. The raw versions are not directly suitable for 3d printing.
  • dromedar_raw_smooth.stl -- infinitely thin, ran through sampler with fairly tight tolerances.

title: LED Christmas Light Inline Resistor Enclosure

description.text:
An old strand of LED Christmas lights lost half its lights and after replacing nearly all of them they still weren't lighting properly. The problem turned out to be the inline resistor which had scorched its PVC container to the point where it was overpowering the LEDs and burning them out. Its container had been destroyed so I put together a replacement suitable for the 1/2W 2500 ohm resistor needed to replace it.

Warning:

While this new container appears to stay cooler than the ones that originally shipped with the strand I expect that as the condition of the LEDs degrade so too will that of the resistor. It already gets hot enough to noticeably soften the PLA/PHA plastic I'm using where it makes contact with the resistor itself. I don't expect that the container is very well suited for outdoor use where it could be exposed to moisture so make sure to adequately seal up the splices with heatshrink as I have demonstrated that the wires and heatshrink will still fit in the holes even unshrunk.

description.text: This is a collection of WS2812B LED rings that I modeled in Fusion 360. If they can be of use in your modeling or just need a stand in before your LED rings come in the mail, here's the STL files I created for my project. Hope it helps you with yours. Rings 1 to 64 are modeled in STL format.

A quick remix of shirley77's Puzzle Ornament to add some future-proofing. Includes years from now (2018) to 2027 (my sincerest apologies to all those viewing this during or after 2028), plus back to 2012 in case you have a use for past years. I also included a blank one so you can be more ambiguous. If you're into that kind of thing. I don't judge. I also converted it to millimeters, since in my experience most slicers use them.

If you happen to want a year (or other short text) that I didn't include, just let me know by either commenting or messaging me. You could also add it yourself to the blank one; I used Impact font, size 9.5pt, and extruded it 1.2mm (in either direction). Happy Printing (or lasering, or FTL travelling, or whatever you're using this for)!

Update 12/28/2017: TinkerWest mentioned that engraved text would also be a nice thing to have, so I've added engraved versions, yay! I also noticed that the file tab was getting a bit cluttered, so I added some .zip folders to help you download convenient selections more quickly. Whoever first said slow and steady wins the race clearly never had to download a lot of files individually. No, seriously, he didn't. He died over 2500 years before the internet or the first file transfer.

comments.text: Cute clever design. An interesting remix would be engraved lettering and then doing a two color print.  First printing one color for the base of letters and then changing colors.  I would do it myself but I'm fortunately I'm waiting for my new printer to arrive.

You could easily do a 2-color print with it as it is! Just swap filament when it starts printing the numbers. I may add engraved versions if I get to it, but if you do a two-color print with engraved letters, one side of each piece will be a different color than the other. That could look super cool, but could also easily look really bad, especially if you didn't anticipate it.

description.text: Ran into an issue where my Dad's diesel wouldn't start one very cold morning. So I went to plug in the block heater and I noticed right away it wasn't going to work because the terminals on the truck side were terribly corroded. So after cleaning those off, I made this to cover the plug in hopes that it wouldn't corrode again any time soon. The strap is made from ninjaflex, so I could get it around the plug. The strap has a small loop and a big loop. The small loop goes onto the 3D printed cover. The big loop is for going around the plug end on the truck side.

FlashForge

Dreamer

Doesn't Matter

No

Notes:

You can use whatever settings you prefer. I printed mine in white abs @230c (heated enclosure) with 3 shells, and 4 top and bottom layers @60mm/s with great success. I didn't need to do any post clean up. I did turn the fans on at the beginning of the top of the knob to help the abs cure better. That helped keep the top knob more uniform.

For the strap I used ninjaflex @245c (heated enclosure) with 2 shells, and top and bottom layers @40mm/s. Turned out good, and wasn't impossible to get it around the plug.

description.text:

Non-printed parts:

  • 10mm M3 button head bolt - 27pcs
  • 8mm M3 bolt - 4pcs
  • M3 lock nut - 26pcs
  • 16mm or longer M3 bolt (for attaching motor to base)
  • 25mm M5 socket head bolt
  • M5 lock nut
  • 625 Bearing
  • 35mm Nylon Standoffs (alternatively these can be printed)

  • Momentary lever switch (same as the ones in mechanical endstops)
  • Superglue (1 drop on the shaft adapter if it's slipping)
  • Hot glue (for gluing down switch in position)
  • Wires, zipties, etc.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1-0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The motor housing prints fine without supports, but might look a little rough from the steep initial overhang. Enable supports+raft to reduce this effect (using a raft for the front motor housing makes it easier to press fit the bearing as well). All pieces are designed to print in the orientation given in the STL files. Print 4 blades, and 1 of everything else (choose the motor mount dimension matching your motor). You'll definitely want to use a brim for the blades.

1. Attach blades to hub using the M3 bolts and lock nuts.
  2. Press fit the 625 bearing into the front motor housing. If the part was printed without a raft, you might need to file the edges of the housing to get the bearing to fit.
  3. attach the rear cage to the front housing with M3 bolts and lock nuts.
  4. Insert the M5 bolt through the bearing from the back of the front housing so that it protrudes out the front.
  5. Put the printed washer onto the bolt, followed by the blade assembly and then the M5 lock nut. The nut should hold the blade assembly securely, without any slipping.
  6. If needed, solder wires onto the motor. The wires should be long enough to run out through the base.
  7. Attach the hex shaft adapter onto the end of the motor spindle. Secure with a zip tie through the hole on the side, and add a drop of superglue if not secure.
  8. Put the motor in the mounting bracket, and adjust its position in the bracket as needed. With the bracket sitting against its mounting points on the front housing, the shaft adapter should fit into the socket on the M5 bolt. When positioned correctly, secure the motor in the mount with an M3 bolt and nut.
  9. Place a lock nut in each of the 3 slots along the outer rim of the front housing.
  10. Place 3 M3 bolts in the screw holes in the rear housing. Stick a hex wrench through the rear access holes to make this easier.
  11. With the front of the fan facing down, place the motor bracket assembly on its mounting point on the front housing. Make sure the motor wire runs through the slot on the edge of the front housing to prevent pinching.
  12. Place the rear housing on top, making sure that the screws align with the holes in the front housing. The motor bracket should be sandwiched between the two housing pieces.
  13. Tighten down the rear housing using a hex wrench through the rear access holes. Make sure the blades turn freely without binding and test that the motor is driving the blades. If there is excessive friction, shift the motor mount a bit and re-tighten. The motor mount is designed to have some slop to allow for alignment, but will be locked in place when tightened down, which could cause binding if improperly positioned.
  14. Run the motor wires through the base.
  15. Secure the motor assembly onto the base using the 16mm M3 bolt and a lock nut.
  16. Attach the front cage using the nylon standoffs and M3 bolts.
  17. Bolt the switch arm onto the base plate.
  18. Wire the switch into the positive wire, configured to turn on when the switch is pressed down.
  19. Glue down the switch such that the printed arm presses the switch when it is moved to the rightmost position. Route the wires through the slot on the back of the base plate, and hot glue them down for strain relief.
  20. Insert a nut into each of the holes on the bottom of the base plate. Bolt the base to the base plate with the 8mm M3 bolts.
  21. (Optional) Solder on a JST or similar connector to the end of the wires.

I always liked those wooden model sailboats made for small ponds and reflection pools; the ones you just put in the water and let sail. The best are Tippecanoe Sailboats, and we have them in a toy store downtown. Still, I'm a lowly, divorced security officer in Seattle and money is so tight I really can't spend like that on toys for my kid. So I designed a boat to print on my machine for his Christmas present. I love how technology solves our problems.

If you do decide to print or have this model printed for your kids, or even for the kid in you, please consider a $5 tip. I do like to keep my models free to download but could always use the help.

Printing Instructions

The Hull and some kind of 1cm diameter ballast pod are practically the only required parts to print. I am going to use a 1/4" machine bolt and nut placed through the ballast lug on the bottom of the centerboard to counterweight my boat. Many free-sailing models omit a rudder, so if it doesn't work that well, just leave it out.

You do need a mast, but any 5mm rod or dowel will work if you don't want to print.

For sails, use whatever material you like. There are small channels at the bow and stern for the strings.

For the ambitious, I have also included the original STEP files as exported from Fusion 360, in case you want to remedy the shortcomings of this version and share it on to others, as well as a STEP model of the hot-end proper if you'd rather start from scratch.

description.text:
OpenForge
=========
Crenelated wall tiles designed to be compatible with Dwarven Forge dungeon tiles. Can be stacked on Stone Corridor Tiles or Stone Wall Tiles with Pillars to create defensive walls.
You can find this set on github
OpenForge Sets
=============
  • Smooth Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc.
  • Smooth Edge Tile Series - Smooth tiles that can be used as concrete, dirt, ice, etc. Edge tiles.
  • Stone Tile Series - Stone tiles.
  • Stone Edge Tile Series - Stone edge tiles.
  • Crenelated Tile Series - Crenelated Tiles
  • Crenelated Edge Tile Series - Crenelated edge tiles
  • Tudor Tile Series - Tudor tiles.
  • Tudor Edge Tile Series - Tudor edge tiles.
  • Ruined Series - Ruined stone walls
  • Accessories - Pillars, etc.
  • Non-Series Tiles - Misc tiles, such as the pool
  • Module Specific Tiles - Tiles designed for specific modules.
    • OpenForge is now a patron supported project. I use the resources that my patrons give me in order to get the resources to let me create more sophisticated tiles with a greater level of detail. Please, support me, and I’ll deliver an ongoing stream of awesome gaming terrain. You can find more about OpenForge and Masterwork Tools at our website, at our forums, or on twitter and facebook.
Painting

Painting was done in 5 layers.
  • Paint whole piece in black
  • Heavily dry brush with a dark grey
  • pick at least one other color (that could be stone) and paint some random stones, front and back.
  • dry brush with grey mixed with a little olive
  • lightly dry brush with a light grey, focusing most heavily on edges

description.text:
So this idea was from the Warlayer Printing and Painting Group on Facebook. You cut a piece of 3mm thick clear acrylic to A6 size. You print overhead transparencies of whatever graphics you like, or clear waterslide decals, and adhere them to either side of the acrylic, ensuring that one side is printed mirrored, to give the illusion of a hologram. You then slide the acrylic down into the frame.

There's 1mm of clearance on each side and bottom, and 0.5mm thickness either side of the acrylic to allow for dimensional tolerances of printers and materials. There's a 5mm bleed for the graphic on each edge, so the actual window is smaller than A6. You want to print so there's say 2mm on each edge inside the frame so that you don';t see the edge of the applique.

title: Adapter to fit Bort BAS-36 battery into SX-CS01-3.6 electric screwdriver

description.text:
This thing is to replace battery in cheap electric screwdriver ("SX-CS01-3.6") with a battery from Bort BAS-36 screwdriver.
Really made just to learn some CAD software.
Assembled from 3 parts - 2 halves form a battery holder, held by 2 screws, and a handle that the holder inserts into. The battery holder also fits to the screwdriver and allows it to rotate the way old handle did.
Included is a model of the battery that would fit. To fit the original one it may be necessary to slightly modify the handle part.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V1

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

100

Notes:

Layer adhesion needs to be good.
Parts could be glued together, but to allow that they need to not warp, so use materials with low shrinkage.
You can print battery holder halves horizontally with a lot of supports from build plate or vertically (sitting on circular flat faces) but with some supports on top of the part, so it could be harder to remove or break something.

If you print this with layer offset of -0.1, it should fit together just fine, but that of course depends on your printer and settings. Make sure overhangs don't warp or clean them up if they do, so the handle fits over other two parts.

To assemble the whole thing, you'll need:

  1. 3 printed parts: BatteryHolderLeft, BatteryHolderRight, ScrewdriverHalf - Handle
  2. some wires
  3. 2 pieces of nickel strip for battery contacts.
  4. soldering iron, etc.
  5. main part of SX-CS01screwdriver with 2 wires coming out
  6. three screws (m3.5, m4 or anything that would fit)

Steps:

  1. Cut a piece of nickel contact strip and fit it into suitable holes on batter holder half, then the same for the other half. Tin and solder the pieces in such a way that they sit securely and would provide good contact with the battery.
  2. stuff two pieces of wire through appropriate holes so wires go from battery contacts to the inside area of battery holder. Solder wires to contacts.
  3. solder wires to the wires going from main part of screwdriver, keeping proper polarity.
  4. stuff wires into battery holder, fit two parts to screwdriver (around the tabs on it), make sure they turn around easily, screw two parts together.
  5. fit the handle over the battery holder, glue it in place or with a small screw that would fit into a hole on it.
  6. check that the battery fits properly.

description.text:
The Made In Shoe’s (MIS) project is an open source, scalable 3D printed shoe manufacture system designed for the low-tech, highly customizable and hyper-local manufacture of highly durable and repairable natural rubber shoes in the developing world.

The MIS system will enable a self-sufficient localized response to many issues in the areas of Sport, Health, Opportunity & Environment and is an example of what can be achieved when communities suffering from aid dependency gain access to the power of 3D printing enabled manufacturing.

Please note this is not a 3D printed shoe project, the shoes are created with latex applied to 3D printed moulds

Notes:

A brim was used to keep the parts secured to the heated bed.

The mould set is fully 3D printable with 3D printed screws. This is so you can scale the mould set to your desired size in your slicer without adjusting the CAD files tolerances. In the gallery you will see an image with three assembled moulds sets:

Right: Original scale - printed with a 0.8mm nozzel at 0.3mm layer height.
Middle: 75% scale - printed with a 0.4mm nozzel at 0.2mm layer height.
Left: 50% Scale - printed with a 0.25mm nozzel at 0.15mm layer height.

Not all scales have been tested but use this as a guide and you should find the correct settings for your size.

Find out more here: https://www.wevolver.com/jonathan.rushton/made-in-shoes/blob/master/documentation.md
